    "cross_module_architecture": {
      "evidence": [
        "Protocol and uploadsvc maintain separate action types/constants and parsers rather than one shared contract boundary (`goseg/protocol/actions/actions.go` defines `Action` + `ActionUploadOpenEndpoint`/`ActionUploadReset`; uploadsvc tests refer to `uploadsvc.ActionUploadOpenEndpoint` and `uploadsvc.ParseAction`).",
        "The adapter layer relies on string casting to bridge the two models (`uploadsvc.Action(action.Action)` and `cmd.Action != uploadsvc.Action(action.Action)`), which creates runtime coupling and hides type-level incompatibilities.",
        "Supported action coverage is validated by test parity loops instead of a package-level shared contract export."
      ],
      "impact_scope": "subsystem",
      "fix_scope": "architectural_change",
      "confidence": "high"
    },
    "high_level_elegance": {
      "evidence": [
        "`Action` contract is spread across at least two modules (`protocol/actions` and uploadsvc) with mirrored names and overlapping semantics, so ownership of action semantics is unclear.",
        "Cross-module alignment is enforced in tests through casts/parity checks rather than explicit API composition (for example, adapter tests iterate protocol action metas and assert translation into uploadsvc command actions).",
        "There is no visible top-level canonical boundary that makes `protocol/actions` and uploadsvc compositionally coupled as intended for a stable domain capability."
      ],
      "impact_scope": "subsystem",
      "fix_scope": "architectural_change",
      "confidence": "high"
    }
  },
  "findings": [
    {
      "dimension": "cross_module_architecture",
      "identifier": "protocol-uploadsvc-action-contract-fragmentation",
      "summary": "Transport action contracts are duplicated across protocol and uploadsvc, creating a hidden drift risk at module boundaries.",
      "related_files": [
        "goseg/protocol/actions/actions.go",
        "goseg/uploadsvc/service_test.go",
        "goseg/uploadsvc/adapters/upload_payload_test.go"
      ],
      "evidence": [
        "protocol/actions defines its own action enum/type (`ActionUploadOpenEndpoint`, `ActionUploadReset`) and parsing helpers.",
        "uploadsvc tests and adapters still rely on local uploadsvc action symbols and translate from protocol symbols with `uploadsvc.Action(action.Action)` casts.",
        "No shared exported constant/type boundary is used between packages in the listed files, so contract consistency depends on test discipline rather than compile-time structure."
      ],
      "suggestion": "Establish a single source of truth for upload actions (e.g., canonical `protocol.Action` as the exported wire contract and reuse it in uploadsvc), or explicitly re-export protocol action constants from uploadsvc via adapter functions so the two packages cannot drift independently.",
      "confidence": "high",
      "impact_scope": "subsystem",
      "fix_scope": "architectural_change",
      "root_cause_cluster": "shared-action-vocabulary"
    },
    {
      "dimension": "high_level_elegance",
      "identifier": "action-parity-tests-mask-ownership",
      "summary": "Cross-module action alignment is represented by parity tests and implicit casts instead of clear module ownership.",
      "related_files": [
        "goseg/uploadsvc/adapters/upload_payload_test.go",
        "goseg/protocol/actions/actions.go",
        "goseg/uploadsvc/service_test.go"
      ],
      "evidence": [
        "Adapter tests call `actions.ActionMetas(actions.NamespaceUpload)` and then assert they map into uploadsvc `cmd.Action` by value casting, so behavior coupling is implicit and spread across tests.",
        "service tests assert exact action slice structure/order from uploadsvc (`len(actions) == 2`, `actions[0] == ...`), which entangles test assumptions with ordering rather than intent.",
        "There is no visible boundary module that advertises the action contract as the authoritative domain exchange format."
      ],
      "suggestion": "Introduce explicit exported protocol contract metadata (e.g., descriptor map with action semantics) and make adapters consume that single surface directly; make tests assert map-keyed compatibility and reject order-dependent checks.",
      "confidence": "medium",
      "impact_scope": "module",
      "fix_scope": "multi_file_refactor",
      "root_cause_cluster": "shared-action-vocabulary"
    }
  ],
  "retrospective": {
    "root_causes": [
      "Dual-maintained action models across protocol/actions and uploadsvc cause ownership ambiguity.",
      "Contract validation relying on tests/casts instead of shared compile-time abstractions."
    ],
    "likely_symptoms": [
      "protocol-uploadsvc-action-contract-fragmentation",
      "action-parity-tests-mask-ownership"
    ],
    "possible_false_positives": [
      "Potentially overstated if uploadsvc intentionally keeps a local command API and protocol package is only for websocket transport parsing; this is not disproven by listed files alone."
    ]
  }
